title: For Sale/Trade:  Colt M1911 A1 (1943) National Match
postcontent:
RARE Colt M1911 A1 early model national match pistol. This is what I know about the gun. Its an original 1943 Colt M 1911 A1 US Army Issue. (matching numbers except slide does not show serial number behind hammer) According to the serial number this gun was shipped to Springfield Armory in February of 1943. It was Issued to an enlisted serviceman at the time. (Trying to find out who it was issued to now through different channels.) There are specific clues on the gun that tell you who it MIGHT have gone to.. There is AA inscribed (Not stamped) on the ivory grips and on the frame Next to GHD. GHD is significant because Col. Guy H. Drewry inspected ordnance from June 17, 1942 to July 15, 1945 For COLT.  

After having multiple collectors and Colt dealers at the gun show look at it. "AA" is believed to stand for "All American" 82nd Airborne Screaming eagles. Which would match the dates the gun was issued, and the eagle carved on the Ivory grips. 82 Airborne was the first Airborne division in US Army history and had three major drops, made their first drop in July of 1943 to invade Sicily. Second was Salerno on 13 September 1943. The third was the invasion of Normandy Jun 1944. 

Not sure how this gun made it back to the states, but it appears the gun was made into a national match pistol during the 1950's or early 1960's, it does not have "NM" stamped on the slide.. BUT NOT ALL PISTOLS BACK THEN WERE STAMPED WITH "NM" for national match. There are two types of Camp Perry National Match pistols.. The kind sent back to Armories and stamped SA for Springfield Armory and NM for Colt Armory. These were tuned, and fitted by the armory for Military camp perry match shooting. The second was private gunsmiths these were done in competition with the armories for the same reason. Many prominent Gunsmiths of the time wanted National match recognition and made their own finally tuned pistols. It appears this one might have been done by a gunsmith. At some point it was re-blued, and fixtures were 24k gold plated and Ivory grips added. It has been determined the gold was added many many years ago as some has worn off in spots. Bluing and finish is still very nice...  Bore is excellent and looks shinning. 

This pistol is a shooter. I have put 100 rounds through it and drives tacks. Its an amazing piece of history and looks beautiful as well. Definitely a one of a kind 1911. Would be a prize piece for any collection. 

I have many pictures if you want more. FTF in tulsa area only.. 4,500$ cash obo.. All reasonable offers considered. Email if interested. Will trade multiple guns.. Please list your offer and values of guns.

title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 71 "Deluxe" .348 Win 1946 348
postcontent: Deluxe" Model 71 Winchester made in 1946, with original sling swivels and sling. The rifle sports a period Redfield receiver sight. The action is as smooth as silk. The bore is bright and shinny. The receiver still has a deep blue mirror finish. The bluing on the barrel is very good. There is some bluing loss on the left side of the forearm cap. The checkering is perfect. The forearm has a couple of light handling marks. The right side of the stock has a light crease and a number of small handling marks about 1 inch in from the pad in the center of the stock. I purchased the rifle in 1988 from the original owner in Klamath Falls, Oregon. I had a gunsmith replace the old pad with a high quality London Guns recoil pad. LOP 13 1/4". I bought the rifle to take an elk with. Just something I wanted to do. I hunted with it, off and on, for several years. In the Fall 1992 I had a big 6 x 6 bull coming down off of a timbered ridge towards me. At about 80 yards I touched off a 250 grain Barnes Original bullet. The bull dropped like it had been hit by a ton of bricks. The rifle has been stored in my gun safe ever since. I will turn 65 this month. I told my wife that the time has come for someone else to enjoy this wonderful rifle. I know these rifles are very collectible and that most of the gunsmiths who built them are gone. But they made them to hunt with. At close range with heavy bullets the .348 Win will dispatch any animal in North America, and dispatch them with ease

title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 71 Pre War Deluxe 1941 NICE 348
postcontent: Original Winchester Model 71 rifles you are likely to find. Serial number 18385 was made in 1941 and is a DELUXE Pre-War short tang rifle. The change over from long tang to short tang took place gradually around the 17000 serial range. As not very many Model 71's were made after 1942, it is quite difficult to find a Pre-War short tang Deluxe Model 71. The ORIGINAL condition of this rifle is outstanding. Excellent stock and fore end with the Pre-War checkering at 20 lines per inch. Nearly ALL of the original varnish and blue remain with some very light high edge wear and handling marks. Original butt plate, original sights and front sight hood. There are NO extra holes or other non-factory alterations. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard. The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil. The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward. You’ll notice in one instance that a shorter barrel gave higher velocities than a longer barrel. This is not a typo.

This load is designed as the world’s premier deer load for the 45 Colt +P. The cast bullet is not considered hard, but neither is it soft. It is essentially a “medium” cast hardness with a BHN (Brinell Hardness Number) of 12. Pure lead is 4 and most hard cast bullets range from 15 to 25. It performs as follows:

At an impact velocity of 1,100 fps it will mushroom to about 80 cal. and should push right through any deer with a broadside shot.

At an impact velocity of 1,500 fps it will mushroom and some of the mushroom will fragment off and send bullet particles flying through the deer, but much of the mushroom and shank will remain intact and should push through any deer hit broadside.

At an impact velocity of 1,900 fps the entire mushroom will turn to shrapnel and send bullet particles all throughout the deer. The shank will remain intact, but will re-mushroom and do horrific damage inside the deer and will probably push through any deer hit broadside.

Of course, results will vary depending on how much bone, if any, is hit, etc... This load was designed specifically to do horrific damage to deer sized animals such as average black bear and hogs. It will make an incredible anti-personnel load if you can handle the recoil. It is flash suppressed and will not blind the shooter if used in low light when the criminal element and wild animals are most active.

The cartridge OAL is 1.585 inch and as such will chamber in any 45 colt firearm such as the Colt SAA or its clones, but firing this +P load in any firearm not designed for it would be disastrous, and could injure the shooter or bystanders. Please be responsible and use this load only in firearms designed to handle the pressure of +P ammunition. Use only in the following firearms:

All Ruger large frame revolvers chambered in 45 colt or 454 Casull. (never use +P ammo in the small frame New Model Vaquero—these revolvers were made from late 2006 and on—do not use in the New Model small frame Flat Top Ruger or ANY small frame Ruger)
All 1892 Winchesters and all copies of such made after 1920.
All Winchester and Marlin 1894 models.
Any break open action such as the T/C or Handi Rifle.
Any falling block action such as the Sharps or Winchester 1895.
Any Freedom Arms model 83 or 97.

If you are not responsible in using +P ammunition only in guns designed for use with +P ammunition, you potentially ruin it for all the responsible shooters that may eventually have +P 45 Colt ammunition removed from the market because of irresponsible use by a few. Please be thoughtful and careful in your firearm selection when using +P 45 colt ammunition.

postcontent:
KSG bullpup shotgun

Caliber 12 gauge 3” 
Barrel length 18.5" 
Total capacity 6+6+1 
Weight empty 6.9lbs 
Weight loaded 8.5lbs 
Length 26.1"

The KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC’s first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3". This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard. The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil. The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward.

If interested please call 604-9733
